ow leading thinkers of the period searched for a humane form of ridicule, one that served the causes of religious toleration, the abolition of the slave trade, and the dismantling of patriarchal power.Ross Carroll brings to life a tumultuous age in which the place of ridicule in public life was subjected to unparalleled scrutiny. He shows how the Third Earl of Shaftesbury, far from accepting ridicule as an unfortunate byproduct of free public debate, refashioned it into a check on pretension and authority. Drawing on philosophical treatises, political pamphlets, and conduct manuals of the time, Carroll examines how David Hume, Mary Wollstonecraft, and others who came after Shaftesbury debated the value of ridicule in the fight against intolerance, fanaticism, and hubris.Casting Enlightenment Britain in an entirely new light, Uncivil Mirth demonstrates how the Age of Reason was also an Age of Ridicule, and speaks to our current anxieties about the lack of civility in public debate.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Apr 2022) 0aEnlightenmentzGreat Britain. 0aRidicule. 7aHISTORY / Europe / Great Britain / General.2bisacsh  aBurke.  aEdmund Burke.  aEnglish Enlightenment.  aFrancis Hutcheson.  aHenry Sacheverell.  aHobbes.  aHumean skepticism.  aJeremy Waldron.  aLawrence Klein.  aLeviathan.  aPerils of False Brethren.  aProtestantism.  aScottish Enlightenment.  aScottish abolitionists.  aShaftesbury and the Culture of Politeness.  aThe Harm in Hate Speech.  aThomas Hobbes.  acomedy.  acultural history.  adissolute mirth.  afeminism.  afree speech.  afreedom of speech.  ahumor.  amockery.  aoffense.  apoliteness.  apolitics of toleration.  apublic sphere.  apublic square.  areligious fanaticism.  aslavery.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE 